Bridgeport Caribe Youth Leaders utilizes sports programming as a gateway to demonstrate to children and their parents the importance of education and civic service. Our objective is to foster an environment where youngsters gain and exhibit confidence and leadership skills in their classrooms, community and families. Participants receive instruction in three (3) major areas: Enrichment Programs (Sports), Educational Programs and Community-based Projects. Throughout each instructional category, participants are encouraged to creatively solve problems, ask for help where necessary, and believe in the validity and power of their own decisions. By creating an environment for our youth to experience the potential of their own choices, program participants learn both accountability and initiative. Most importantly, our continuum of services prepares youth for adulthood, successful careers and lifelong learning. Hence our motto, Building Today's Youth...Tomorrow's Leaders

Oxfam Mexico is part of the international Oxfam Confederation, a global movement working in 94 countries to build a future free of poverty and injustice. Worldwide, one out of three people lives in poverty. Oxfam is determined to change this, by mobilizing the power of people. In Oxfam Mexico we work to achieve a fairer country:
  • Ensure food security to the population and the sustainable use of resources;
  • Create opportunities for local economic development in migrant communities;
  • Respond to emergencies caused by disasters;
  • Impulse informed public policy based on a development approach and promote active citizenship;
  • Promote the empowerment of women for the creation of a more egalitarian society.
Oxfam Mexico, in partnership with migrant organizations, has joined efforts to promote the participation and leadership of young women in productive local companies, in their organizations and in their work and advocacy initiatives. Oxfam has supported this effort since 2007 in the state of Zacatecas, and in 2010 we started working in other Mexican states such as Guanajuato, Oaxaca y Tlaxcala. In 2012 we expanded our scope to Puebla and Chiapas and in 2013 to Hidalgo.

México es hoy en dóa el paós con míçs migrantes alrededor del mundo. De acuerdo con las cifras del Banco Mundial para 2010, México ocupó el primer lugar en nómero de emigrantes con 11.9 millones. Anualmente 500 mil mexicanos migran hacia Los Estados Unidos, el 72% de ellos son jóvenes menores de 29 años, de los cuales 73% son hombres y 27 % son mujeres.
El fenómeno migratorio estíç asociado a la bósqueda de empleo y mejores ingresos para mejorar su nivel de vida. Para todos, jóvenes y adultos, la bósqueda de empleo digno es una de las razones por las que ésta población emigra, lo cual tiene un impacto notable en la vida social, económica y cultural, en las comunidades de origen. La pobreza y exclusión obliga a los jóvenes a buscar nuevas oportunidades.

NSNP reaches the community through the individual child. Our theory of community change is that by focusing on a child, he or she will affect change in his or her life, his or her house, and then expand to the school, block, street and eventually, the community. Through this change process, we have been able to affect positive change in generations of community residents. In order to bring this spirit of youth-driven change within the organization as well, we have increased youth decision-making within our programs and program design, as youth from kindergarten to the twelfth grade contribute to the development of program activities on an age-appropriate scale.

An integral part of the NSNP programming is providing a small program model in which a familial environment exists between staff (most of whom are community members), youth, and other community members. We value the individualized attention and relationships instructors engage in with youth and the positive influence this has on youth development and educational advancement. Many youth have taken this mentoring and support to become mentors, themselves. We have hired program participants as staff members and interns, and we have worked with older youth to prepare them for board service.

Our history began on the 2100 block of North Howard Street, in the West Kensington section of North Philadelphia, in 1973, when a local fifth grade teacher and a professor at Eastern University founded NSNP. The two women collaborated with volunteer teachers, artists and community residents to create an educational center that was culturally relevant to, and protective of, the children living in a section of Philadelphia that was notorious for its deadly drug culture. Our work has grown in scope as the predominantly Latino community around us has expanded. Our environmental and cultural education programs have helped transform the community and the lives of Latino Norris Square residents.

NSNP’s service in the community has provided residents with an intergenerational gathering space where children, parents and grandparents join together to learn and grow. We attribute our success to the support of the community and to longstanding collaborations past and present, including Grupo Motivos (a Puerto Rican women’s collective), Eastern North Philadelphia Youth Services Coalition, Mural Arts Program, Pennsylvania Horticultural Society, PhillyCam, Taller Puertorriqueño, University of Pennsylvania, and many more.

Norris Square Neighborhood Project (NSNP) is an arts and gardening organization, serving youth and adults in programs focused through the lens of Latino culture. Our mission is to promote positive change through youth education, community leadership, green spaces, the arts and the celebration of Latino culture.

Norris Square Neighborhood Project (NSNP) is an arts and gardening organization, serving youth and adults in programs focused through the lens of Latino culture. Our mission is to promote positive change through youth education, community leadership, green spaces, the arts and the celebration of Latino culture.

Vacant lots are a prevalent problems throughout Philadelphia, and Norris Square is no stranger to the issue. The gardens had been empty spaces in the neighborhoods - magnets for crime, drug use, and destitution. However, that changed over twenty years ago with the creation of Las Parcelas, Colobo, Raices, and Batey. The gardens serve as inspiration to community members, as well as refuge from the day-to-day. Las Parcelas unites community members and showcases the valuable work community members have done to revitalize a neighborhood once plagued by violences and decay.

Today, Las Parcelas continues to address multiple issues ranging from food insecurity to lack of quality hands-on education. Las Parcelas is a living museum, learning environment, communal space, and place to demonstrate sustainable food production. With the support of the public, we can preserve this space and continue to offer environmental, cultural, and arts-based education to the public and community members of Norris Square.

Founded in 1974 by Latino artists and activists in the North Kensington area of Philadelphia, Taller Puertorriqueño (Taller) stands as testament to the wealth of possibilities created when citizens see a need in their community and decide to meet it. Discouraged by the absence of outlets for Barrio youth desperate to channel their artistic talents, Taller’s founders created a community-based graphic arts workshop to provide cultural training alternatives to local youth. The idea of passing along traditional culture to help empower young people through pride in their heritage was and remains central to this workshop. Today, in Philadelphia’s Barrio and throughout the region, Taller Puertorriqueño is a force for change, building community through art. Taller’s programs have expanded to include the following:
  • Cultural Exploration Program introduces young students to renowned local artists

Taller Puertorriqueño, Inc. (Taller) is a community based cultural organization whose primary purpose is to preserve, develop and promote Puerto Rican arts and culture, grounded in the conviction that embracing one’s cultural heritage is central to community empowerment. Taller is also committed to the representation and support of other Latino cultural expressions and our common roots.

Taller Puertorriqueño, Inc. (Taller) is a community based cultural organization whose primary purpose is to preserve, develop and promote Puerto Rican arts and culture, grounded in the conviction that embracing one’s cultural heritage is central to community empowerment. Taller is also committed to the representation and support of other Latino cultural expressions and our common roots.

Taller asserts that there are significant unmet community needs side by side with identified community opportunities that support our vision to build a center for economic and social activity in the heart of Philadelphia's Latino Community. This project transforms an urban surface parking lot into a hub for the community, El Corazón Cultural Center, a crossroads where people come together. We aim for the new center to use the arts as an engine to showcase and promote the richness and beauty of Puerto Rican and Latino arts and cultures, celebrate and promote our community, and create an environment of commercial, tourism, marketing and cultural opportunities.

We plan to build a 24,000-square-feet facility on a 2.25-acre site transferred from the city for this purpose through a City Council resolution. The site is in the heart of the Latin Barrio and at the entrance of the Golden Center (El Centro de Oro) 5th Street commercial district. Taller presently occupies two buildings at 2721 N. 5th Street and 2557 N. 5th Street bisected by Lehigh Avenue, an oversized east-west arterial road that severs connection between the Centro de Oro retail corridoräóîthe area with the largest concentration of Latino-owned businesses and Latino organizationsäóîand Taller's primary sphere of operation.

The research on summer learning loss points to a disturbing relationship between socioeconomic, racial/ethnic disparities, and the achievement gap. (Georgia Family Connection Partnership - Research Brief May 2012). Many students fall behind by an equivalent of 30% of their previous year learning. Additionally, due to socioeconomic challenges, many families are unable to enroll their students in any type of physical activity programs or camps. Young students begin to develop a sedentary lifestyle that can potentially lead to health challenges commonly seen in Latino adults such as diabetes and other illnesses. LAWA seeks to promote physical activities to promote healthy lifestyles.

SLI is a student-run, student-led program of the Center for Global Initiatives at UNC-Chapel Hill. Two student co-directors are elected annually to coordinate the activities of approximately 75 UNC sophomore, junior and senior mentors selected in their sophomore year. The SLI model focuses on four core components: 1) one-on-one mentoring; 2) community service; 3) the College Prep Seminar (CPS), a college level course designed to expose mentees to the rigor of college-level classes; and 4) SLI SMART (Skills Making Applicants Ready for Tomorrow), a college prep class. In addition to these core components, mentors lead and/or participate in the following committees: Development, Visual Communications, Parental Involvement and Community Building (events focused on peer support and engagement).

UNC mentors also serve as site coordinators for six high school sites in Chatham County, Lee County, Orange County, Durham County and Randolph County . They work with selected teacher liaisons at each school who are responsible for coordinating program logistics/persistence and completion.

UNC faculty and staff are extensively engaged in SLI. The “college seminar” is taught by faculty. Faculty and staff working and teaching across the academic spectrum (e.g. admissions, chemistry, education, public health, journalism) actively participate on SLI’s Board of Directors, which meets monthly. A part-time program coordinator serves as SLI’s staff.

Finally, SLI helps to secure scholarships for SLI students through an awards process managed by a committee composed of community members.

SLI's mission is to promote educational equity and diversity by providing Latino students the tools to access higher education. SLI accomplishes its mission by engaging high-potential Latino high school students in a structured three-year mentoring and college preparatory program that promotes academic excellence, leadership, community involvement and personal integrity. In addition, SLI identifies and helps to provide scholarships to students with financial needs and negotiates leveraged support from colleges and universities for its mentees. Through SLI, mentees develop an enthusiasm for higher education and are better prepared for college success.

Founded in 1995, the Hispanic Liaison of Chatham County's mission is to
foster cultural understanding among Latinos and other residents of Chatham
County, and to empower Hispanics to overcome the challenges they face as
immigrants and find their voice in the community.  We serve over 5,500 individuals each
year.  We achieve our mission through our
three core programs: Community Services Program, Youth Leadership Development
Program, and our Income Development Center. Our programs foster community
self-sufficiency and empowerment by increasing access to information and
services; youth leadership and civic engagement, and economic and community development. Our vision is to create a
thriving and just community in which Latinos are visible, welcome, and
empowered participants in all aspects of society. We work with local government, law enforcement, service and other non-profit organizations. Our partnerships help strengthen our program delivery and impact, allowing our achievements to reverberate across the county.

Homies Unidos has served over 6700 youth and parents through presentations and workshops in schools, community centers, and conferences. We developed two cornerstone programs that are interlinked to create opportunities for at-risk, gang-involved youth and their immigrant families to take control of their lives, neighborhoods and advocates for social change and justice to influence public policy. Our efforts have been widely reported in local, national and international media (NPR, al Jazeera, TV Azteca, Nation Magazine, Univision, etc.).
  • Sep 19, Organized the Central American Youth Leadership Conference, for unaccompanied minors in the school system.
  • We graduated 57 Central American newly arrived youth fleeing violence through our Joven Noble Youth.
  • Summer, Unaccompanied Minors present for the first time in public at the Social Workers Center to a group of Central American activist. Then they made interviews in KPFK 90.7FM, La Opinion, Univision, The Nation and more.
  • Summer 2015, seven youth who graduated from our Joven Noble program participated in our Youth Leadership Training.
  • We have Continued taking families to advocate for their love ones to Sacramento to meet with the Governor’s representatives and the Department of Correction and Rehabilitation (CDCR)

Homies Unidos ha servido más de 6700 jóvenes y padres a través de presentaciones y talleres en escuelas, centros comunitarios y conferencias. Homies Unidos mission: To end violence and promote peace in our communities through gang prevention; the promotion of human rights in immigrant communities and the empowerment of youth and families in El Salvador and Los Angeles to achieve their full potential in a just, safe and healthy society.

Youth and community members express distrust of law enforcement's overly harsh responses and fear that police collaborate with immigration authorities; while at the same time, law enforcement and police officers express frustration that they äóìare unable to take proactive steps to build relationships in the communityäó. Despite 46 arrests per 1,000 residents in the area surrounding the Rampart Police Station in 2008, the lack of an effective strategy to create safety has resulted in over 30 active gangs with nearly 3,000 members, continuing a cycle of disproportionally targeting our youth through ineffective policies, criminalization and deportation.

Simultaneously, the increasing number of deportations is increasing family separations and family economic hardships. Most recently, On October 11, 2012 the Treasury Department formally designated MS-13, or Mara Salvatrucha, a transnational criminal organization. The impact in our predominately Central American community has been of a continued presence of law enforcement and immigration officers targeting and labeling our youth. This has behavioral changes in older children who have had parents deported or incarcerated which often include increasing aggressiveness, particularly if the parents were arrested at the home, which in turn leads to increasing crime and law enforcement issues. Community violence also leads to a community caught in a vicious cycle of recidivism and destructive behaviors.

To address these issues, Homies Unidos works to end gang violence and state violence and to promote peace in our communities by empowering youth and their families to become advocates for social justice rather than agents of self-destruction.

Through our Leadership development and other services provided through Homies Unidos such as Tattoo removal, we have geared our youth from hopelessness to empowerment by providing them with life skills program as well as redirecting their energy to express themselves through community organizing.

As members of more than one historically marginalized group, queer youth of color face special challenges in a society which often presents heterosexuality as the only acceptable orientation. Moreover, these youth face the often complicated terrain of navigating the intersections of their ethnic, cultural, and sexual/gender identities, with little to no support or resources. Compared with peers from families that reported no or low levels of family rejection, queer young people who reported higher levels of family rejection during adolescence were 8.4 times more likely to report having attempted suicide, 5.9 times more likely to report high levels of depression, 3.4 times more likely to use illegal drugs, and 3.4 times more likely to report having engaged in unprotected sexual intercourse. Latino men, in comparison with non-Latino men, reported the highest number of negative family reactions to their sexual orientation in adolescence. Another study showed that while bisexual and lesbian teenage females were about as likely as heterosexual peers to have had intercourse, they reported twice the rate of pregnancy as heterosexual and questioning young women.

A nationwide study of homophobia in schools found that the majority of queer youth of color had experienced victimization in school because of either race or sexual identity in the last year, while half reported being victimized because of both race and sexual identity.

Lastly, queer youth of color report feeling pressure to choose between their ethnic and their sexual identities; these youth are less likely to be involved in gay social and cultural activities than their white counterparts. (Sources: Bridges, E., MLS. The Impact of Homophobia and Racism on GLBTQ Youth of Color. Advocates for Youth. July, 2007; Ryan, C. et al. Family Rejection as a Predictor of Negative Health Outcomes in White and Latino Lesbian, Gay, and Bisexual Young Adults. Pediatrics, Vol 123, No. 1 January 1, 2009 pp.346-352.)

This information clearly demonstrates that Latino queer youth are particularly vulnerable. Currently, there are no programs in Philadelphia designed specifically to meet the needs of queer Latino youth. The Outlet program has already demonstrated the ability to effectively provide resources, support and programming that directly addresses the intersections of identity that queer Latino youth face.

Latinos are the fastest growing school-aged population both nationally and in North Carolina, yet many of them perform far below most of their peers from the first day of kindergarten. 36% of children entering kindergarten in Durham identified as Hispanic/Latino,[1]Although a majority of Latino children were born in the United States[2], national evidence has found that Latinos are less likely than children of any other racial or ethnic group to be enrolled in an early childhood program or to receive early intervention services.[3] Access to high quality early education is crucial for gaining the skills needed to start kindergarten ready.

The mission of Clónica Esperanza/Hope Clinic is to offer high quality medical care and preventive health services to adults and children* living in Rhode Island who do not have health insurance or cannot afford to purchase health care. Because many people do not speak English as a first language, Clónica Esperanza/Hope Clinic places special emphasis on linguistically competent, culturally attuned care. In addition, our focus is on prevention and health maintenance, which reduces the need for our patients to be hospitalized for preventable illnesses.

Clónica Esperanza/Hope Clinic is managed by highly qualified and experienced volunteer health providers and community representatives, and supported by an all-volunteer administrative staff. The Clónica Esperanza/Hope Clinic is a place where bright new ideas about improving access to healthcare are welcome. Our motto is Healthy People, Healthy Community.

Clónica Esperanza/Hope Clinic does not discriminate among applicants for care on the basis of age, gender, race, religion, national origin, disability, sexual orientation or marital status.

Non-urgent healthcare problems are responsible for more than 9 million visits to emergency departments (ED) in US hospitals each year, largely due to patients' lack of access to a primary care physician. To avoid costly and unnecessary ED usage for non-urgent health problems and improve access to health screens for low-income, uninsured individuals affected by Health Disparities* , a walk-in clinic run by a nurse manager and staffed by volunteers was developed as an extension of the primary care medical services provided by Clinica Esperanza/Hope Clinic (CEHC). 

Establishment of La Bodega, also known as äóìCHEERäó (CEHC ER-diversion), has made it possible for more than 1000 uninsured patients to be seen for non-urgent health problems over the past 18 months. La Bodega provided basic health screens and offered routine vaccinations to these individuals in addition to addressing their healthcare needs. 

The impact of this intervention on the local economy has been significant: Based on local estimates of $761 per ER visit, La Bodega saved low-income patients more than $321,571 in ER costs in 2013. 

The return on investment was $37 per $1 of funding, including QALY (quality adjusted life-years), based on early estimates (Bicki et al. Dec. 2013 [http://bit.ly/Nurse_Run_CHEER ]) and utilization numbers for 2013.

While our request involves a specific project, donations will support Calpulli Community overall. The opportunity here is to support one of very few year-round, high-quality learning, arts, and culture programs in the Northeastern USA. Calpulli Community is not recreational; it is an active training program for aspiring artists. Without continuous support for the program and its projects, our organization struggles to continue to serve more students at the same level of quality.

High quality is defined by the experienced, passionate Teaching Artists, professional studios and support staff, and by the practices that align Calpulli with learning standards that are challenging to achieve and gratifying to exceed.

The mission of the Young Center is to promote the best interests of unaccompanied immigrant children with due regard to the child's expressed wishes, according to the Convention on the Rights of the Child.

Every young immigrant deserves to be safe. The Young Center is a champion for the best interests of children who arrive in the United States on their own, from all corners of the world. We serve as trusted allies for these children by accompanying them through court proceedings, advocating for their best interests, and standing for the creation of a dedicated juvenile immigrant justice system that ensures the safety and well-being of every child.

The Young Center for Immigrant Children's Rights is a project of the Tides Center, a 501c3.

La misión del The Young Center es promover los mejores intereses de los menores inmigrantes no acompañados con la debida atención a los deseos expresados por el niño, de acuerdo con la Convención sobre los Derechos del Niño.
Cada joven inmigrante merece ser salvo. The Young Center es un defensor de los mejores intereses de los niños que llegan a los Estados Unidos por su cuenta, de todos los rincones del mundo. Servimos como aliados de confianza para estos niños acompañándolos a través de los procedimientos judiciales, defendiendo de sus intereses, y de pie para la creación de un sistema de justicia juvenil dedicada inmigrante que garantice la seguridad y el bienestar de todos los niños.

A March 2014 United Nations report found that the majority of Central American children coming to the U.S. on their own are fleeing situations in their home countries so dangerous and violent that they would be eligible for international protections. However, the current influx of children arriving at the border has prompted the government to announce that it will soon require children to proceed with their deportation hearings within weeks of arriving, many still detained in custody, separated from family, and completely on their own. The majority of these children will not have attorneys or Child Advocates by their side.

The Young Center wants to provide the most vulnerable children with Child Advocates, guardians ad litems, who can ensure children are not repatriated to dangerous situations. We currently only have offices in Chicago and the Rio Grande Valley in Texas. If we are successful in our goal, we will be able to deploy Child Advocates to serve children in need in New York, Houston, and the D.C. area.

LSC fue fundada en 1975 como una de las primeras firmas de abogados sin fines de lucro dedicada a prestar servicios gratuitos de representación legal y trabajo social a los niños y los adolescentes. Es nuestra misión garantizar que todos los niños del zona de la Bahía de San Francisco crezcan en un entorno sano con igualdad de acceso a una buena educación y otros servicios necesarios para prosperar y crecer. Combinamos la importancia de la experiencia jurídica con los servicios totalmente integrados de trabajo social diseñados para satisfacer las necesidades solapadas de cada cliente. LSC es una pionera en este enfoque interdisciplinario que se considera la mejor práctica en derecho juvenil.

One can't turn on the television or read a newspaper without hearing about the recent influx of unaccompanied undocumented minors crossing our borders. The figures are nothing short of alarming, with the US government now estimating that 60,000 unaccompanied children (UACs), primarily from Central America, will enter the US in the 2013-2014 fiscal year--three times the number of children who came here the year before. This does not even begin to account for the untold numbers of youth who manage to evade detection and live beneath the legal radar in our communities, at risk for deportation.

These children come to the US in desperation, endeavoring to escape abuse, neglect, exploitation, persecution, gang violence or horrific poverty. They are particularly vulnerable due to their ages, their separation from adult caretakers, and the dangerous journeys they endure. If detained, they face the deportation process without any right to a lawyer. The vast majority of those who are not apprehended subsist in poverty without a stable home and few opportunities for education or employment. Far too many of these children are forced to traffic drugs into the US or are sexually exploited.

A great many of these youth qualify for legal status through programs created especially for their needs--special immigrant juvenile status (SIJS) for abused and abandoned youth, U-Visas (for victims and witnesses of serious crimes), T-Visas (for victims of trafficking) or asylum. LSC's services are a lifeline to the youth detained in Northern California or living in the Bay Area. Without access to legal counsel, children are forced to represent themselves in court with its highly complex laws and adversarial nature, effectively losing out on a variety of legal remedies... and hope for the future.

Founded in 2010, the New Mexico Immigrant Law Center is the only legal service organization in New Mexico dedicated to preventing separation of families due to deportation. In addition to ensuring family unity, we seek to strengthen immigrant families by advancing the rights and opportunities of low-income immigrants and their families. We envision a New Mexico in which all people äóñ regardless of their race, immigration, or economic status äóñ have equal access to justice, as well as access to education, government resources, and economic opportunities, and are able to engage fully in the civic and economic life of our neighborhoods and community.

Access to high-quality immigration services provided by NMILC enables immigrants to obtain legal status that can lead to better jobs, access to credit and bank accounts, reunification with family members, access to healthcare, increased educational opportunities for children and adults, and full participation in the civic life of our neighborhoods and communities. While gaining immigration status brings a certain level of economic and family stability, naturalization creates opportunities for newcomers to fully participate in the civic life of their communities.

The New Mexico Immigrant Law Center is committed to providing high-quality legal representation in complex immigration cases, with an emphasis on assisting particularly vulnerable populations, such as children. NMILC is the only nonprofit immigration legal services provider in New Mexico which provides representation to individuals in removal proceedings, including children applying for SIJS. Therefore, for many of the types of cases involving immigrant children, NMILC is the only option.

The mission of NMILC is to make access to justice affordable for New Mexico’s immigrants and aspiring citizens and to promote knowledge of legal rights and the immigration process. NMILC believes that all people, regardless of their financial status, should have equal access to legal information and due process.

As an member-led immigrant rights organization, this issue is very important to us. Our members  are saddened by the plight of these children and disappointed by the way the matter is being treated by national elected officials. That said faith communities, lawyers, local allies and our members are stepping up to try to help locally in Massachusetts. Our task is to help educate the public, provide immediate support to immigrants and advocate on their behalf at a local and national level. If Congress won't act, it is up to us to take action!

Since 1988, Casa Alianza Mexico (CAM) has served children and adolescents between the ages of 12-18, who are homeless, abused, neglected and abandoned by society. As a result of working with such a population CAM has developed a deep knowledge of the integral difficulties that confront socially abandoned children on their path to recuperating a sense of identity, self-worth, and responsibility for their own futures. CAM is one of the leading experts in Mexico on issues of at-risk youth. As a key government partner and child advocate, FCAM has played a significant role in advancing legislation in Mexico to serve unaccompanied abandoned migrant children.

We are part of an international network led by Covenant House International. Along with Nicaragua, Honduras and Guatemala; Casa Alianza gathers up efforts to protect socially abandoned children and adolescents.Thus, in recognition of our daily hard work Casa Alianza Mexico has been awarded with the Conrad N. Hilton Humanitarian Award, the Olof Palme Award, Luis Elizondo Award, the Quetzalcoatl Award, the Reina Sofía Award and a sign agreement with the national Commission for Refugee Support (in recognition to our work with migrants).

Our mission is to assist and support socially abandoned children and adolescents on their journey to achieve their potential and become productive members of society.

EBSC’s mission is to provide sanctuary, including protection, advocacy, and support, and capacity building to low-income and poverty stricken refugees and immigrants. For more than 30 years, EBSC has offered sanctuary and support to low-income and indigent immigrants and refugees.  We provide free or low-cost necessary immigration legal services, social services, and psychological support to clients from over 60 countries.  Our staff of 16 includes five immigration attorneys (four staff attorneys and one legal fellow) and two BIA-accredited representatives.  EBSC also enjoys the generous support of over 128 volunteers, including 77 law students, many from the UC Berkeley School of Law.

La misión de EBSC es proporcionar santuario, incluyendo la protección, defensa y apoyo, así como crear capacitación para refugiados e inmigrantes de bajos ingresos y afectados por la pobreza. Durante más de 30 años, el EBSC ha ofrecido refugio y apoyo a los inmigrantes indigentes y los refugiados de bajos recursos. Proporcionamos servicios gratuitos o de bajo costo necesarios para cuestiones legales de inmigración, así como servicios sociales y apoyo psicosocial a clientes de más de 60 países. Nuestro personal de 16 incluye cinco abogados de inmigración (quatro abogados de planta y uno becario legal) y dos representantes acreditados por la BIA. EBSC también cuenta con el generoso apoyo de más de 128 voluntarios, entre ellos 77 estudiantes de derecho, muchos de ellos de la escuela de derecho de UC Berkeley.

Our organization was formed to serve the uninsured in our community. Even with the Affordable Care Act (ACA) it is estimated that there remain 550,000 people in the Denver Metro community that simply cannot afford insurance. We also serve undocumented people who may be in our community temporarily or on a more permanent basis. 70% of our patient base identifies as Hispanic/Latino/Mexican. We have a variety of primary care practice programs that serve entire families. Our programs include: Adult Wellness, Well Child Exams, Well Woman Exams, Cancer Screenings, Prenatal Care, Counseling and Chronic Illness Management.

In 2013 we served 3,937 individual patients through 9,517 office visits. We have two full-time medical providers on staff, with three medical assistants, two medical receptionists and two patient navigators. We have one full-time administrative position and our two counselors work on a contract basis. We also have ten medical providers that volunteer their time, usually once a month to see patients within our practice.

Through a partnership with St. Joseph hospital, we also have midwives give prenatal care and deliver babies.

Our mission is protect and advance the rights of immigrants and their families through legal representation in immigration and criminal court as well as community advocacy. We are one of the first non-profits in the nation to protect the rights of non-citizens through immigration and criminal defense representation.

Nuestra misión es proteger y promover los derechos de los inmigrantes y sus familias a través de la representación legal de la inmigración y el tribunal penal, así como la promocion de la comunidad. Somos una de las primeras organizaciones no lucrativas en el país para proteger los derechos de los no ciudadanos a través de la inmigración y la representación de defensa criminal.

Children are not provided attorneys in deportation proceedings, meaning they are required to defend themselves alone against the prosecutor and the judge. 9 out of 10 children will be deported without attorneys, whereas 100% of SJC's minor clients have won their cases. 

Many of these children will be killed if deported to their countries.

Founded in 1969, Centro Legal de la Raza in Oakland is a comprehensive legal service agency focused on strengthening low-income, immigrant, and Latino individuals and families by providing culturally competent legal representation, education, and advocacy. It provides direct legal services in the areas of immigration, housing, and employment. Centro Legal’s immigration practice is focused on serving the needs of the most vulnerable community members, including families living in poverty, women, children, and victims of violent crimes including domestic violence and detained individuals in removal proceedings. Its offers comprehensive, full-service direct representation, legal rights education, and client intake through various immigration clinics. The organization specializes in detained and non-detained removal defense, affirmative asylum applications, family-based visa petitions, U visas for victims of violent crime, and naturalization.

  • Heketi Community Charter School
  • Amani Charter School
  • Avance Charter School
As Convener the Foundation co-led the Steering Committee for the Bronx Borough President's first Education Summit.
As Strategic Partner, the Foundation helped launch the Latino Charter Leaders Roundtable, an affinity group of community-grown charter school districts in New York City.

La Fundación colabora con Aprendes , apoya y financia a grupos comprometidos con la búsqueda de soluciones locales a los problemas de la comunidad .
La Fundación AprenDes orienta su trabajo en estas tres áreas programáticas :
Educación y Participación de la Comunidad
Alianzas Estratégicas
Recaudación de Fondos / Patrocinio Fiscal

  • New York Charter School Incubator
  • Heketi Community Charter School
  • Amani Charter School
  • Avance Charter School
Como coordinador, la Fundación co - dirigió el comité de dirección de la primera Cumbre de Educación del Presidente de El Bronx.
Como socio estratégico , la Fundación ayudó a lanzar los líderes Charter Latino Roundtable , un grupo de afinidad de los distritos de escuelas charter crecido en la comunidad en la ciudad de Nueva York .

Schools today must meet increasingly rigorous standards while serving a more racially, ethnically, socio-economically, and linguistically diverse student population than ever before. The new academic demands coupled with the rapid growth in the number and proportion of children of immigrants and students who are English language learners (ELL) require that schools find new ways to educate their students and prepare them to take full advantage of the opportunities in the twenty-first century knowledge economy and for civic participation in society. Charter schools are one of a range of educational reform strategies that school districts across the country use, in part, to respond to these demands. 

Community-grown charter schools, led by Latinos promises to shed light on culturally competent approaches to community engagement in education.

Las escuelas de hoy debe cumplir con las normas cada vez más rigurosas mientras cumplía una más racial, étnica , socio- económica y población estudiantil lingüísticamente diversa que nunca. Las nuevas exigencias académicas , junto con el rápido crecimiento en el número y la proporción de hijos de inmigrantes y estudiantes que están aprendiendo inglés (ELL ) requieren que las escuelas a encontrar nuevas formas de educar a sus estudiantes y prepararlos para sacar el máximo provecho de las oportunidades en el XXI economía del conocimiento del siglo y de la participación ciudadana en la sociedad . Las escuelas charter son una de una serie de estrategias de reforma educativa que los distritos escolares en todo el país el uso , en parte, para responder a estas demandas .
Escuelas charter crecido en la comunidad , dirigidos por latinos promete arrojar luz sobre los enfoques culturalmente competentes a la participación comunitaria en la educación.

Compañeros is an organization that serves the Hispanic and immigrant communities, that creates positive relationships with other non'profit organizations, churches, businesses, governmental y law enforcement agencies and the community in general to find solutions to find solutions to the problems that affect our community.  We believe in the power of the people and we know that a people who makes its own decisions prospers.  That´s why we promote and support the community so that it may find its voice and leads itself.  Our impact can be seen in the community members who have participated in a Know Your Rights training, our free state and federal tax preparation service, and those that have been able to access medical services, housing and other resources through our help.
a:2:{i:0;s:43:\A majority of the management team is Latino\";i:1;s:55:\"A majority of the people serving on the Board is Latino\";}"
Compañeros' mission is to create positive social change by supporting Latinos and immigrants and their loved ones through advocacy, education, and integration programs.

Compañeros es una organización que sirve a las comunidades hispana e inmigrante, que forma relaciones positivas con otras organizaciones sin fines de lucro, iglesias, negocios, agencias de gobierno y de cumplimiento de ley y la comunidad en general para buscar soluciones para los problemas que afectan a nuestra comunidad.  Creemos en el poder del pueblo y sabemos que un pueblo que toma sus propias decisiones prospera.  Por eso fomentamos y apoyamos a la comunidad para que encuentre su voz y se dirija sola.  Nuestro impacto se ve en los miembros de la comunidad que han participado en los talleres de Conozca sus Derechos, la preparación de impuestos estatales y federales a través de nuestro servicio gratuito, y que han podido acceder a los servicios sanitarios, vivienda y otros recursos a través de nuestra ayuda.

This project addresses what has been a widespread problem, individual immigrants driving without licenses or having no state identification, with a new opportunity presented as a result of the Colorado 2013 legislative session. As mentioned previously, our state passed the Community and Road Safety Act that year and implementation began in August of 2014. Compañeros quickly learned that the Department of Revenue only partially funded the implementation of this Act resulting in limited office locations, insufficient staff and language access. For the immigrants of our communities, most of them Hispanic or Latino, this lack of sufficient and nearby resources means they have to take a major risk in order to apply for a driver's license. As Compañeros is the only resource center for this population in the area, and the only non-profit organization doing anything to inform the public about this Act, its requirements and benefits, we believe Compañeros is the only entity able to facilitate the goal of this project.

Esto proyecto aborda un tema que ha sido probelmático en muchas partes: inmigrantes indivíduos que manejan sin licencia o que no posean identificación estatal.  Lo abordamos a través de una nueva oportunidad que se presentó como resultado de la sesión legislativa de Colorado de 2013.  Como anteriormente mencionada, nuestro estado aprobó la Ley de Seguridad en las Comunidades y las Carreteras en ese año y la implementación se puso en marcha en agosto de 2014.  Poco tiempo después, Compañeros se enteró que el Departamento de Hacienda sólo otorgó una parte de los fondos requeridos para implementar esta ley, lo que se llevó a un número límitado de oficinas disponibles y una falta de personal y de servicio en español.  Para los inmigrantes de nuestras comunidades, Hispános o Latinos en su mayoría, esta falta de recursos suficientes y cercanas conlleva un riesgo significativo para poder solicitar una licencia de conducir.  Dado que Compañeros es el único centro de recursos para esta población en nuestra región, y la única organización sin fines de lucro que educa al público con respeto a esta ley, sus requisitos y beneficios, creemos que Compañeros es la única entidad que pueda facilitar la meta de este proyecto.

Casa de la Amistad para Niños con Cáncer covers the full cost of pediatric cancer treatment, including medication. Since our founding, we have contributed to giving life and hope to 7,660 children and adolescents diagnosed with cancer. In our 24 years, Casa de la Amistad (CDLA) has invested $34,160,656 USD in oncological care. But we do much more than that. We believe that when a child is hospitalized the love and care of family is as powerful as the strongest medicine prescribed, which is why we also assist patients nationwide with a “home-away-from-home” at no cost, so families can remain united while their child is hospitalized. Our “home-away-from-home” offers: · Three nutritionally home-cooked meals. · Accredited education programs for children and family members. · Psychosocial support services. · Recreational activities and spaces, such as workshops and playgrounds. · Transportation to and from place of origin, and to all hospital visits. · Special suites for children with suppressed immune systems. · Private bedrooms. In addition to these services and in order to reach more, we have a network of medicine banks that distribute medications and supplies to hospitals, non-profits and other Casa de la Amistad medicine banks. Our allies then provide these to our beneficiaries. We work directly with 21 hospitals located in 17 different states and 8 hospitals located in in Mexico City. 100% of the families we attend at considered low income; 28% of these families have an extremely low social economic level (measured as a combination of education, income, and occupation), 64% of them belong to a low social economic class, 8% to a medium-to-low and 1% from middle-class families. Furthermore, 68% of our beneficiaries reside in Mexico´s most rural and poverty-stricken states, where basic medical care is nonexistent. In search of healthcare, families are obligated to travel outside of their communities, often up to 521 miles away in Mexico City.
Increase Mexico´s childhood cancer survival rate by sponsoring treatment, building capacity in medical communities and providing supportive services to families.

Nuestro albergue cuenta con 48 habitaciones y 108 camas que permiten a nuestros niños tener un lugar cómodo donde hospedarse durante su estancia en la Ciudad de México, les ofrecemos los tres alimentos del día cuidadosamente preparados para favorecer su tratamiento, pueden iniciar y terminar sus estudios de primaria, secundaria y preparatoria en nuestra escuela donde además capacitamos en braille a aquellos niños que requieren ese apoyo especial. Contamos con pedagogas y psicólogas que ofrecen respaldo educativo y apoyo emocional con un enfoque resiliente. Nuestro programa de apoyos médicos cubre todo el tratamiento oncológico, estudios especiales, prótesis, Endoprótesis y todo lo requerido por el médico tratante. Todos nuestros servicios son 100% gratuitos. Todos nuestros niños pertenecen a familia en pobreza extrema por lo cual nuestro apoyo es su única esperanza para recuperar su salud de otra forma existirán posibilidad nulas de sanar. Hemos formalizado un convenio de colaboración con St. Jude´s Children´s Research Hospitalcon la finalidad de capacitar médicos y enfermeras en Chiapas, el estado mexicano más afectado por esta enfermedad. Adicional hemos apoyados a la investigación de tumores con el hospital siglo XXI y actualmente con Dell Inc. hemos desarrollado una red inter médica en el estado de Chiapas que permite a los médicos compartir casos y diagnosticar oportunamente de forma remota. Esta red intercomunica a zonas muy alejadas del Estado para diagnosticar y definir protocolos más certeros.

México se enfrenta a una serie de obstáculos que contribuyen directamente al bajo índice de sobrevida:
 1. Diagnósticos tardíos producidos por la falta de conocimiento de los signos y síntomas del cáncer infantil entre padres y doctores de primer contacto.
2. Deficiente infraestructura y falta de recursos necesarios para el tratamiento del cáncer.
3. Abandono del tratamiento generado por el alto costo del mismo y la falta de recursos de familias de escasos recursos.

ConTextos prepares students in El Salvador to be critical thinkers capable of confronting the region's most urgent problems.
 We do this through an innovative teacher-training program, the creation of libraries, a unique writing program that incorporates tablet technology, and diverse partnerships.
a:2:{i:0;s:43:\A majority of the management team is Latino\";i:1;s:55:\"A majority of the people serving on the Board is Latino\";}"
Transform the educational experience so students go beyond rote memorization, to develop authentic literacy skills such as deep thinking, analysis and creativity.

ConTextos prepara a los estudiantes en El Salvador para ser pensadores críticos, capaces de confrontar los problemas más urgentes de la región.
Hacemos esto a través de un programa innovador de formación docente, la creación de bibliotecas y un programa único de escritura que incorpora la tecnología de tablets y diversas colaboraciones.
With this project we will be able to enrich the collection of the libraries and we will collect data to analyze the replicability of the project.
Con este proyecto enriqueceremos la colección de las bibliotecas y recolectaremos datos que nos permitirán analizar la capacidad de replicar este proyecto.

Plan Pais is a non-profit organization dedicated to providing educational services related to the progress of Venezuela. Furthermore, it aims to encourage political and civic participation among the Venezuelan youth, promote an innovative, progressive and impartial debate with the purpose of creating a vision for the long run of Venezuela as well as facilitate the creation of a network of young professionals abroad.

Cada año la conferencia se lleva a cabo en distintas Universidades, y en estos ultimos cuatro años, hemos podido impactar a mas de 500 jovenes profesionales y estudiantes que han participado en la conferencia. Es realmente increible la red profesional y de amigos que se produce de los participantes de la conferencia.

All previous editions of Plan Pais had been held in the east coast of the United States. This 5th edition of Plan Pais, the conference will be held in Texas and we have imposed ourselves the challenge of incorporating the views of Venezuelans from the west of the United States and other parts of the country that had not been represented in the conference before and has now become easier to attend the conference because of its centric location.

Anteriormente, ediciones pasadas de Plan Pais han sido en la costa del este de los Estados Unidos. Esta 5ta edición de Plan Pais sera llevada a cabo en Texas y nos hemos impuesto la meta de incorporar la vision de los estudiantes Venezolanos residentes del area del oeste de los Estados Unidos y de otras partes del pais que no habian sido representados en las discusiones ya que a muchos se les facilitara asistir la conferencia por su ubicacion centrica.

Calpulli Mexican Dance Company's mission is to produce dance-based programming incorporating live music and theater to promote the rich diversity of Mexican and Mexican-American culture. To this end, the organization produces professional performances via its touring company, designs arts-in-education programming, and leads Calpulli Community.

Calpulli Danza Mexicana tiene la misión de producir programación a base de la danza incorporando la música en vivo y el teatro para promover la riqueza de la herencia cultural Mexicana y Mexico-Americana. Con este fin, la organización produce presentaciones al nivel profesional por medio de su compañía, diseña programas de las artes en educación, y es líder de Comunidad Calpulli.

Enseña por El Salvador is a team of teachers, policy makers, education professionals and social entrepreneurs from El Salvador, the US, and Finland. Together with the Ministry of Education and in partnership with local schools and communities, we are igniting a movement of outstanding leaders who will reshape their country and believe that we can rebuild and create a better future. Students who have traditionally been from the most under-resourced public schools will have access to an education that is engaging, community-based, and conducive to deep learning.

At Enseña por El Salvador, we believe in the inalienable right to a quality education for all children, regardless of their socioeconomic background. Everyday we work in order to uphold that right. We fundamentally believe that a quality education is an invaluable tool for marginalized children to access opportunities and have a better quality of life. At a country level, we believe that our commitment to a quality education will enable us to break the cycle of poverty, establish more integrated communities, and reduce crime rates and violence. In order to achieve this goal, we need everyone to be part of the solution and form alliances across multiple sectors

Igniting a movement of empowered leaders who are committed to making a promise for a better tomorrow.

"

Enseña por El Salvador está trabajando por atraer, seleccionar, formar y asignar a los mejores profesionales salvadoreños para trabajar durante dos años en el aula. Actualmente necesitamos desarrollar el instituto de formación que preparará a los jóvenes profesionales como docentes de clase mundial y enfocado en la innovación, inspirado en el modelo de Teach for All.

A nivel de país, creemos que nuestro compromiso con la calidad educativa nos permitirá romper el ciclo de pobreza, promover comunidades más integradas y reducir índices de violencia en el largo plazo. Para alcanzar este objetivo necesitamos que todos sean parte de esta solución y construir alianzas entre diferentes sectores de la sociedad.

Enseña por El Salvador es un equipo de profesores, impulsadores de políticas públicas, profesionales de la educación y emprendedores sociales de El Salvador, Estados Unidos y Finlandia. Junto al Ministerio de Educación y en asocio con escuelas locales y las comunidades, buscamos encender un movimiento de jóvenes profesionales líderes capaces de dar una nueva forma a su país. Creemos que podemos reconstruir y crear un mejor futuro a través de la educación. Estudiantes que tradicionalmente han estado dentro de escuelas públicas con pocos recursos y pocos docentes tendrán acceso a una educación comprometida, basada en la comunidad y atada a un aprendizaje significativo y profundo.

Mission, history and major developments
Founded in 1987 to address the devastating impact of pregnancy on low-income Puerto Rican teens in Hartford’s Frog Hollow neighborhood, Family Life Education (FLE) is an independent non-profit organization that strives to empower city families to transform circumstances of poverty into opportunities for growth, learning and self-efficacy. Our mission is building a stronger community by fostering partnerships that engage families in a participatory process leading to self-efficacy. Specifically, we help at-risk families to develop the confidence and skills to chart their own life courses, on their own terms. To accomplish these aims, FLE provides leadership development, culturally sensitive parenting education, developmental assessment/child care, peer mentoring, counseling, outreach and support. Services are geared to families, children and youth throughout the city. The majority are of Latino heritage, including first and second generation Puerto Ricans, as well as immigrants from Latin/Central America.
 Recently, the organization implemented a new service delivery model that assists youth, parents and families to attain their full potential. To be infused through all of our programs, the model emphasizes self-awareness, personal responsibility and empowerment as critical first steps in achieving self-efficacy. To avoid dependency, FLE avoids participants repeating program cycles, thereby encouraging them to go on to the next stage of their personal development, whether a job, a GED program, vocational training, or saving to rent a better apartment. Ultimately, the aim is to support them in taking charge of their own and their children’s lives, and to develop the critical thinking and problem solving skills needed to become productive, responsible and engaged citizens. Continued support is offered to those who desire it after the program engagement period ends.
 FLE’s constituency stretches across low-income communities in more than 15 nearby towns in the 29-town area, with the majority (98%) residing in Hartford. Towns include, among others: Bloomfield, East Hartford, Windsor, Manchester and West Hartford. Our doors are open to anyone in need; we do not turn anyone away.
Facility Space
The Children’s Wellness Center will be located in the Parkville neighborhood, which is Hartford’s most ethnically diverse. It will be housed in 4,000 sq. feet on the ground floor of 30 Arbor Street South, immediately underneath FLE’s administrative offices. The space has abundant sunlight, with large windows that were recently installed by the property owner. The HVAC system was also recently updated by the property owner, meaning heating and cooling will be available year-round. Finally, the property owners have floated a new cement floor. Overall, they have invested roughly $150,000 in the space because of their enthusiasm about the project and its role in local economic development. The facility will have two entrances, and full handicap accessibility. Formerly a storage area without insulation or heat, the space must undergo full renovations in order to be used as a Children’s Wellness Center. Already, $125,000 has been raised. We need to raise an additional $75,000 to complete renovations.
Collaborating Organizations
Over the past year, Family Life Education has worked with many different organizations and institutions in the planning and development of the Children’s Wellness Center. While some have visited our location and met with staff, others have committed to provide services within the Center, which will mean lowered staffing costs for the facility. All continue to support the successful establishment of the Center. These entities are as follows:
  • The ThinkWell Center
  • University of Connecticut Agricultural Extension Program
  • Cooking Matters
  • My City Kitchen
  • Windowfarms Garden Project
  • Connecticut Children’s Medical Center
  • Hartford Children’s Wellness Alliance
  • Hartford Food System
  • Department of Children, Families, Youth and Recreation, City of Hartford
  • Department of Health and Human Services, City of Hartford
  • Dept. of Anthropology, University of Connecticut
  • Institute for Community Research
  • 30 Arbor Street, LLC (property owners)
Because cognitive learning is the most important pillar of the new Children’s Wellness Center, this program is conceived as a permanent one going forward. Thus, FLE is committed to raising funds that will sustain it. Already, we have won the support of Congressman John Larson, Dr. Myra Jones-Taylor, Commissioner of the Ct. Office of Early Childhood, and Dr. José Colon, head of the City’s Dept. of Children, Families, Youth and Recreation. Mayor Segarra has endorsed the project, and committed $50,000 to the last phase of renovations. Our intention is to seek program support from the Administration of Children, Youth and Families, the U.S. Dept. of Education, and the Ct. Dept. of Education. In addition, we intend to explore opportunities from national foundations like Edna McConnell Clark, Ford, and Kellogg. FLE has a strong base of support from the faith-based community that will be tapped, as well as an active body of volunteers from the corporate sector and general public. They will be enlisted to undertake fundraisers, mail solicitations, and establish a “Friends of the Children’s Wellness Center” group. Finally, the facility is designed to generate income through rentals for birthday parties, cultural celebrations, workshops and other events. Last, our board is discussing the possibility of opening a consignment shop to garner revenue for the Children’s Wellness Center.

Building a stronger community by fostering partnerships that engage families in a participatory process leading to self-efficacy.

Mission, history and major developments
Founded in 1987 to address the devastating impact of pregnancy on low-income Puerto Rican teens in Hartford’s Frog Hollow neighborhood, Family Life Education (FLE) is an independent non-profit organization that strives to empower city families to transform circumstances of poverty into opportunities for growth, learning and self-efficacy. Our mission is building a stronger community by fostering partnerships that engage families in a participatory process leading to self-efficacy. Specifically, we help at-risk families to develop the confidence and skills to chart their own life courses, on their own terms. To accomplish these aims, FLE provides leadership development, culturally sensitive parenting education, developmental assessment/child care, peer mentoring, counseling, outreach and support. Services are geared to families, children and youth throughout the city. The majority are of Latino heritage, including first and second generation Puerto Ricans, as well as immigrants from Latin/Central America.
 Recently, the organization implemented a new service delivery model that assists youth, parents and families to attain their full potential. Latinos/as experience multiple challenges that interfere with healthy growth and development of their children.  These challenges include sociocultural, linguistic and racial isolation, as well as severe poverty, limited formal education (and English language skills), low- and pre-literacy in Spanish, lack of transportation, lack of knowledge about early childhood milestones, and poor access to existing resources.  In that many families are recent arrivals to the U.S., they are not familiar with Hartford or the educational, health care, transportation and legal systems.  Finally, they are unaware of available social services, free English language classes, children's and other resources available in the community--and how to navigate them. 

According to an article titled, äóìThe Early Catastrophe,äó by Hart and Risley, äóìOne of the biggest challenges of this new environment is the feeling of being confined.  Another challenge is security.äó  Latinos are used to warm climates, and spending long hours outside.  While crime exists in their home countries, the violence that exists here is unknown to many.  Thus, parents often do not allow their children to walk to school or go to the park, leading to lack of exercise, long hours of TV watching and a sedentary lifestyle.  Exacerbating these circumstances is the fact that cultural mores about childrearing emphasize keeping children within the family until school age.  Leaving a child with someone who is not a family member is unacceptable. Further, the concept of pre-school is foreign.  Yet in view of the daunting challenges faced by low-income immigrant families, intervention is critical.  Parents need support, education about appropriate developmental milestones for their children, and a place to turn for help if the child is not talking, acting out or unresponsive.  In addition, parents need to feel comfortable with turning to non-family members for assistance.  Last, parents need to understand how critical the early years are to a child's development, and the importance of pre-school for ensuring the child's cognitive growth and preparedness for school.  In that the majority of families served by FLE come to the U.S. so their children äóìcan have a better life,äó education is prized.  Thus, the opportunity to ensure children have the best possible educational foundation is a profound motivation for parents.

Note Hart and Risley: äóìWithin a child's early life the caregiver is responsible for most, if not all, social stimulation and consequently language and communication development.  As a result, how parents interact with their children is of great consequence given it lays a critical foundation impacting the way the children process future information many years down the road.äó This study displays a clear correlation between the conversation styles of parents and the resulting speech of their children. This connection evidences just how problematic the results of this study may truly be. The finding that children living in poverty hear fewer than one-third of the words heard by children from better off families has significant implications in the long run. When extrapolated to the words heard by a child within the first four years of their life these results reveal a 30 million word difference. That is, a child from a better off family will experience 30 million more words within the first four years of life than a child from a low-income family. This gap does nothing but grow as the years progress, ensuring slow growth for children who are economically disadvantaged and accelerated growth for those from more privileged backgrounds.

In addition to a lack of exposure to these 30 million words, the words a child from a low-income family has typically mastered are often negative directives, meaning words of discouragement.  The ratios of encouraging versus discouraging feedback found within the study, when extrapolated, evidences that by age four, the average child from a family on public assistance will hear 125,000 more words of discouragement than encouragement. When compared to the 560,000 more words of praise as opposed to discouragement that a child from a high-income family will receive, this disparity is striking.

äóìA 2005 report in the New England Journal of Medicine startled the nation with its prediction that the current generation of children will be the first in America to have a shorter lifespan than their parents' generation äóñ due largely to obesity-related disease.

This dire prediction was supported by a recent report by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) that found that approximately two-thirds of U.S. adults and one-fifth of U.S. children are obese or overweight. According to the CDC, during 1980 to 2004, obesity prevalence among U.S. adults doubled, and it increased substantially among children. In addition, African Americans have a 51% higher prevalence of obesity, and Hispanics have 21% higher obesity prevalence compared with whites.

When low-income minority children are not properly prepared for school and/or suffer from delays, their lives are destined for a very different trajectory than if they are school ready. Connecticut dumps $605 million a year warehousing inmates, most of whom are functionally illiterate.  According to a 2007 Hartford Courant article titled, äóìGet Kids Reading, And Early,äó by Stan Simpson, äóìYou could draw a straight line between reading achievement in third grade, the rate of graduation in the 12th grade and the rate of  incarceration.äó  Former Cincinnati schools Chief Steven Adamowski goes on to argue, äóìA student who is not reading at grade level in Grade 3 has the life prospect at best of working poverty äóñ and at worse, a life of incarceration.  Adomowski's assessment of the system he inherited in Hartford is that it is fixable.  The best way to transform Hartford schools äóñ and to measure success is to put extra attention on grades 1 through 3.   

References:  Hart, B. & Risley, T.R. äóìThe Early Catastropheäó (2004). Education Review, 77 (1), 100-118. <http://www.gsa.gov/graphics/pbs/The_Early_Catastrophe_30_Million_Word_Gap_by_Age_3.pdf>; School Literacy and Culture http://literacy.rice.edu/slc/owl-lab 
Simpson

Teach For Mexico is part of the international network Teach For All with 35 partners and growing with the model of leadership and training. Teach for Mexico has also formed strategic partnerships with the secretaries of public education in Puebla, Guanajuato, and Nuevo León to bring our teachers' impact to the classrooms. Likewise we have partnered with other organizations like ALFA, CONALEP, and ENOVA in order to place our teachers in school programs serving under-resourced school areas. This has allowed our program to spread to 5 states with 210 teachers and 35 staff members. These teachers teach over 12,000 students across these 5 states. In order to support these teachers in our program they are put into teams of 17 to 20 with an academic tutor leading the team in charge of their professional and classroom skills development. Teachers are given monthly trainings in order to develop these professional and classroom skills. The alumni leadership team manages their transition out of the program and focuses on their continued development as advocates of educational and social equity.

The current project will be headed up by the team of tutors and the training team with its design and execution. This team comes from 7 countries including Argentina, Mexico, the US, Spain, Chile, Peru, and Colombia and brings a world of experience and perspective to the table!
a:3:{i:0;s:28:\Executive Director is Latino\";i:1;s:43:\"A majority of the management team is Latino\";i:2;s:55:\"A majority of the people serving on the Board is Latino\";}"
Teach For Mexico aims to create, train, and support a network of leaders, who work collaboratively in order to create an impact both in and out of the classroom while working towards social justice.

Enseña por México es parte de la red internacional Teach For All con 35 socios y en crecimiento con el modelo de liderazgo y formación. Enseña por México también ha formado alianzas estratégicas con los secretarios de educación pública en Puebla, Guanajuato y Nuevo León para traer impacto de nuestros maestros a las aulas. Del mismo modo nos hemos asociado con otras organizaciones como ALFA, CONALEP y ENOVA con el fin de colocar a nuestros profesores en los programas escolares que sirven de en zonas escolares de bajos recursos. Esto ha permitido que nuestro programa se extienda a 5 estados con 210 profesores y 35 miembros del personal. Estos maestros enseñan a más de 12.000 estudiantes en estos 5 estados. Para apoyar estos maestros en nuestro programa que se pongan en equipos de 17 a 20 con un tutor académico que lleva el equipo a cargo de su desarrollo de habilidades profesionales y de clase. Los maestros reciben capacitaciones mensuales para desarrollar estas habilidades profesionales y de clase. El equipo de ex alumnos de liderazgo dirige su transición fuera del programa y se centra en su continuo desarrollo como defensores de la equidad educativa y social.

El actual proyecto será dirigido por el equipo de tutores y el equipo de formación con su diseño y ejecución. Este equipo viene de 7 países, entre ellos Argentina, México, los EE.UU., España, Chile, Perú y Colombia y trae un mundo de experiencia y perspectiva a la mesa!

Mexico faces a situation where the leaders needed to confront educational inequity on a systemic level is drastically underrepresented than the demand that society presents. The summer InVe is the platform where we start our leaders on a journey to not only participate in changing the trajectory of students through academic engagement and transformational classrooms but also fill in the gap that exists in Mexican society of leaders who understand the major components of social inequality. This gap in human capital with an intimate understanding of educational inequity is what we aim to close by giving these would-be teachers a strong start to creating a transformational classroom. Teach For Mexico's InVe is an amazing opportunity for students to receive rigorous academic instruction based on real-world skills, while training the next generation of leaders to form a vision, develop solution-oriented thinking, and manage their time effectively.

México se enfrenta a una situación en la que los líderes que se necesitan para hacer enfrentar desigualdad educativa a nivel sistémico son drásticamente subrepresentados a la demanda que la sociedad presenta. El InVe es la plataforma en la que iniciamos a nuestros líderes en un viaje para participar no sólo en el cambio de la trayectoria de los estudiantes a través del compromiso académico y aulas transformadoras, sino también llenar el vacío que existe en la sociedad mexicana de líderes que entiendan los componentes principales de la vida social desigualdad. Esta brecha en capital humano con una comprensión íntima de la inequidad educativa es lo que pretendemos cerrar dando a estos aspirantes profesores un fuerte inicio de la creación de un aula transformadora. El INVE de Enseña por México es una oportunidad increíble para que los estudiantes reciben instrucción académica rigurosa basada en las habilidades del mundo real, mientras que la formación de la próxima generación de líderes para formar una visión, desarrollar el pensamiento orientado a las soluciones, y gestionar su tiempo eficazmente.

La Esperanza del Mañana, works on 5 main themes with different programs and projects in 9 municipalities in the Northeast Sierra of Puebla. Environment. In nine years we have produced 7 million trees for reforestation programs. We have built over 350 ecological stoves for the same number of families, reducing the consumption of fire wood. Food Security. We have implemented over 17 vegetable gardens in over 17 schools, training more than 700 students in building vegetable gardens. Education. We train students in the management of the backyard and vegetable gardens. We built 5 subjects for the State´s high school program, focused on Backyard Agriculture. Since August 2010, there are 295 high schools in Puebla applying this training. Along with a private University in Puebla, we developed a scholarship program to young people committed to their rural communities, in order to go to college and contribute to the development of their region. Currently 39 students have graduated and there are 50 studying. Since 2009 we have implemented a program to improve schools. To date we have improved over 27 schools building bathrooms, classrooms, water tanks, etc. This program has benefited over 2,000 children. Tourism. We have also developed a program to improve the urban image of populations, through painting houses, construction of sidewalks, etc, as a trigger of community tourism. We have improved the image of 11 communities impacting over 3000 people. Taltokalis Training Centre. The experience of 10 years, mainly in environment, food security, and education, has led us to propose a broader and larger scale project. Taltokalis is set in an area of 40 hectares which are reorganized into a demonstrative productive space. We seek sustainability to the functioning and operation of the Centre so it does not depend but only of labor and products generated in there. The education and training of learning by doing, allows participants to have the tools and skills to be employed as technicians, keep studying, and / or generate their own self rural enterprise. It is noteworthy that all this do not be possible without the participation of entities of different levels of government. We also have the support of national foundations such as Fomento Social Banamex, Alfredo Harp Helú Foundation, Community Foundation of Puebla, Puebla Produce Foundation, and international such as Hispanics in Philanthropy and Vista Hermosa Foundation.
